Avoid locking and reopening logfile in runtime logger of Test::Unit

The following code has some problems at least on Windows:
```ruby
File.open('a-file', 'r') do |f|
  f.flock(File::LOCK_EX)
  File.open('a-file', 'a') { |f2| f2.puts('text') }
end
```

I think it's better to open just a single file descriptor and apply
lock on it. This approach fixes specs on Windows.

Use ParallelTests.with_ruby_binary only for bin/parallel_* binaries (#590)

* Use ParallelTests.with_ruby_binary only for bin/parallel_* binaries

This change fixes rake tasks on Windows. The only place where adding
ruby binary is necessary for bin/parallel_* binaries. For all other
cases it may leads to some ambiguous command lines like
`ruby.exe ruby rake` which don't work.

* Use ruby binary prefix only for bundler stubs

It turns out that using path to binaries relative to the source
code is not the best practice. On Windows rubygems generates .bat
files for every binary during gem installing. However it doesn't
help if we try to locate and run binary relative to the source
code.

This change removes all such usages, so running parallel_*
binaries will work on Windows and on Linux the same way. The only
place we still need prefixing with ruby.exe is bundler's binstubs.

* Fix tests

* Don't use Shellwords.escpace where it's not necessary

* Restore using relative path during call parallel_* binaries

* Revert "Fix tests"

This reverts commit a6c3137

Convert specs to RSpec 2.99.2 syntax with Transpec

This conversion is done by Transpec 3.1.0 with the following command:
    transpec

* 239 conversions
    from: obj.should
      to: expect(obj).to

* 175 conversions
    from: == expected
      to: eq(expected)

* 64 conversions
    from: obj.should_receive(:message)
      to: expect(obj).to receive(:message)

* 35 conversions
    from: obj.stub!(:message)
      to: allow(obj).to receive(:message)

* 18 conversions
    from: =~ /pattern/
      to: match(/pattern/)

* 16 conversions
    from: stub('something')
      to: double('something')

* 15 conversions
    from: obj.should_not
      to: expect(obj).not_to

* 12 conversions
    from: pending
      to: skip

* 10 conversions
    from: mock('something')
      to: double('something')

* 10 conversions
    from: obj.stub(:message)
      to: allow(obj).to receive(:message)

* 6 conversions
    from: =~ [1, 2]
      to: match_array([1, 2])

* 5 conversions
    from: obj.should_not_receive(:message)
      to: expect(obj).not_to receive(:message)

* 4 conversions
    from: be_true
      to: be_truthy

* 2 conversions
    from: lambda { }.should
      to: expect { }.to

* 1 conversion
    from: < expected
      to: be < expected

* 1 conversion
    from: >= expected
      to: be >= expected

* 1 conversion
    from: be_false
      to: be_falsey

For more details: https://github.com/yujinakayama/transpec#supported-conversions

operations listed here:

http://ruby-doc.org/core-1.9.3/Encoding.html#method-c-default_internal

Updating cucumber / gherkin runner

Currently when using --group_by scenarios option gherkin runner generates command which outputs same feature files multiple times for instance:

cucumber features/feature1:10 features/feature1:14 features:feature2:13

This causes cucumber to call before_feature multiple times on the same feature within one thread. This is not desirable and a knock on effect is that junit reporter is broken as it overwrites feature files with the last execution.

This change fixes this by combining same features:

cucumber features/feature1:10:14 features:feature2:13
Add option to pass in location of runtime log

Much more even algorithm for distributing tests between processes

When there is large variation in how long tests take to run, the old
algorithm could be very uneven in its distribution.  This replaces it
with a greedy algorithm that assigns each test to the process
with the lightest workload.  I don’t think it’s provably optimal,
but it performs much better.  Example:

Before:

size[1] = 531.661853
size[2] = 471.283475
size[3] = 512.337818
size[4] = 519.610019
size[5] = 528.156902
size[6] = 513.50903
size[7] = 646.904167
group size 0 = 1
group size 1 = 2
group size 2 = 3
group size 3 = 5
group size 4 = 9
group size 5 = 15
group size 6 = 25
group size 7 = 231
8 processes for 291 specs, ~ 36 specs per process

group size 0 = 30
